# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: plsql
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:plsql/oracle-database] It is commonly used for online transaction processing (OLTP), data warehousing (DW), and mixed database workloads.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] As a converged database, it supports multiple data models within a single engine, including relational, JSON document, XML, spatial, graph, text, and vector data, all queryable through SQL.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle Database runs on-premises, on Oracle engineered systems such as Oracle Exadata, on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, and as a managed Autonomous Database service.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] It is also offered inside Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud, and Amazon Web Services data centers through Oracle's multicloud offerings.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] The current long-term release is Oracle AI Database 26ai, which was introduced in October 2025.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Larry Ellison and his two friends and former co-workers, Bob Miner and Ed Oates, started a consultancy called Software Development Laboritories (SDL) in 1977, later Oracle Corporation.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] SDL developed the original version of the Oracle software.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] The name *Oracle* comes from the code-name of a Central Intelligence Agency-funded project Ellison has worked on while formerly employed by Ampex; the CIA was Oracle's first customer, and allowed the company to use the code name for the new product.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Ellison wanted his database to be compatible with IBM System R, but that company's Don Chamberlin declined to release its error codes.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] By 1985 Oracle advertised, however, that "Programs written for SQL/DS or DB2 will run unmodified" on the many non-IBM mainframes, minicomputers, and microcomputers its database supported "Because all versions of ORACLE *are* identical".
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle Corporation held its initial public offering on March 12, 1986.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] The company grew rapidly during the 1980s, though a financial setback in 1990 led to its first quarterly loss and significant layoffs before the business recovered.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle7, released in 1992, matured the product into a leading enterprise relational database management system, adding persistent PL/SQL stored procedures and triggers, a cost-based query optimizer, and improved administration tools.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle Database 12c (2013) introduced the multitenant architecture and the In-Memory Column Store, with "c" denoting "cloud".
[src:plsql/oracle-database] In 2017 Oracle announced Oracle Autonomous Database, a self-managing cloud service, with the first services becoming available in 2018.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Beyond the on-premises editions, Oracle Autonomous Database automates provisioning, tuning, patching, and scaling and is offered in data-warehousing and transaction-processing variants.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle products follow a custom release-numbering and -naming convention.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] The "ai" in the current release, Oracle AI Database 26ai, stands for "Artificial Intelligence".
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Oracle Database 19c, 10g, and Oracle9i Database) have used suffixes of "c", "g", and "i" which stand for "Cloud", "Grid", and "Internet" respectively.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Prior to the release of Oracle8i Database, no suffixes featured in Oracle AI Database naming conventions.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] There was no v1 of Oracle AI Database, as Ellison "knew no one would want to buy version 1".
[src:plsql/oracle-database] For some database releases, Oracle also provides an Express Edition (XE) that is free to use.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] The Introduction to Oracle AI Database includes a brief history on some of the key innovations introduced with each major release of Oracle AI Database.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] See My Oracle Support (MOS) note *Release Schedule of Current Database Releases (Doc ID 742060.1)* for the current Oracle AI Database releases and their patching end dates.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Prior to Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation released Critical Patch Updates (CPUs) and Security Patch Updates (SPUs) and Security Alerts to close security vulnerabilities.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] These releases are issued quarterly; some of these releases have updates issued prior to the next quarterly release.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] Starting with Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation releases Release Updates (RUs) and Release Update Revisions (RURs).
[src:plsql/oracle-database] RUs usually contain security, regression (bug), optimizer, and functional fixes which may include feature extensions as well.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] RURs include all fixes from their corresponding RU but only add new security and regression fixes.
[src:plsql/oracle-database] However, no new optimizer or functional fixes are included.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL includes procedural language elements such as conditions and loops, and can handle exceptions (run-time errors).
[src:plsql/pl-sql] It allows the declaration of constants and variables, procedures, functions, packages, types and variables of those types, and triggers.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Arrays are supported involving the use of PL/SQL collections.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Implementations from version 8 of Oracle Database onwards have included features associated with object-orientation.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] One can create PL/SQL units such as procedures, functions, packages, types, and triggers, which are stored in the database for reuse by applications that use any of the Oracle Database programmatic interfaces.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The first public version of the PL/SQL definition was in 1995.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The main feature of SQL (non-procedural) is also its drawback: control statements (decision-making or iterative control) cannot be used if only SQL is to be used.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL provides the functionality of other procedural programming languages, such as decision making, iteration etc.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A PL/SQL program unit is one of the following: PL/SQL anonymous block, procedure, function, package specification, package body, trigger, type specification, type body, library.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Program units are the PL/SQL source code that is developed, compiled, and ultimately executed on the database.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The basic unit of a PL/SQL source program is the block, which groups together related declarations and statements.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A PL/SQL block is defined by the keywords DECLARE, BEGIN, EXCEPTION, and END.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] These keywords divide the block into a declarative part, an executable part, and an exception-handling part.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The declaration section is optional and may be used to define and initialize constants and variables.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] If a variable is not initialized then it defaults to NULL value.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The optional exception-handling part is used to handle run-time errors.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The symbol `:=` functions as an assignment operator to store a value in a variable.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Blocks can be nested – i.e., because a block is an executable statement, it can appear in another block wherever an executable statement is allowed.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A block can be submitted to an interactive tool (such as SQL*Plus) or embedded within an Oracle Precompiler or OCI program.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The interactive tool or program runs the block once.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The block is not stored in the database, and for that reason, it is called an anonymous block (even if it has a label).
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The purpose of a PL/SQL function is generally used to compute and return a single value.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] This returned value may be a single scalar value (such as a number, date or character string) or a single collection (such as a nested table or array).
[src:plsql/pl-sql] User-defined functions supplement the built-in functions provided by Oracle Corporation.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A function should only use the default IN type of parameter.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The only out value from the function should be the value it returns.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Procedures resemble functions in that they are named program units that can be invoked repeatedly.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The primary difference is that **functions can be used in a SQL statement whereas procedures cannot**.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Another difference is that the procedure can return multiple values whereas a function should only return a single value.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The procedure begins with a mandatory heading part to hold the procedure name and optionally the procedure parameter list.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Next come the declarative, executable and exception-handling parts, as in the PL/SQL Anonymous Block.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The example above shows a standalone procedure - this type of procedure is created and stored in a database schema using the CREATE PROCEDURE statement.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A procedure may also be created in a PL/SQL package - this is called a Package Procedure.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A procedure created in a PL/SQL anonymous block is called a nested procedure.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The standalone or package procedures, stored in the database, are referred to as "stored procedures".
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Procedures can have three types of parameters: IN, OUT and IN OUT.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The program assigns the parameter value and that value is returned to the calling program.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] An IN OUT parameter may or may not have an initial value.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] That initial value may or may not be modified by the called program.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Any changes made to the parameter are returned to the calling program by default by copying but - with the NO-COPY hint - may be passed by reference.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL also supports external procedures via the Oracle database's standard `ext-proc` process.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Packages are groups of conceptually linked functions, procedures, variables, PL/SQL table and record TYPE statements, constants, cursors, etc.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The use of packages promotes re-use of code.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Packages are composed of the package specification and an optional package body.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The specification is the interface to the application; it declares the types, variables, constants, exceptions, cursors, and subprograms available.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The body fully defines cursors and subprograms, and so implements the specification.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Using package variables one can declare session level (scoped) variables since variables declared in the package specification have a session scope.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A database trigger is like a stored procedure that Oracle Database invokes automatically whenever a specified event occurs.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] It is a named PL/SQL unit that is stored in the database and can be invoked repeatedly.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Unlike a stored procedure, you can enable and disable a trigger, but you cannot explicitly invoke it.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] While a trigger is enabled, the database automatically invokes it—that is, the trigger fires—whenever its triggering event occurs.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] While a trigger is disabled, it does not fire.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] You create a trigger with the CREATE TRIGGER statement.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] You specify the triggering event in terms of triggering statements, and the item they act on.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The trigger is said to be created on or defined on the item—which is either a table, a view, a schema, or the database.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] You also specify the timing point, which determines whether the trigger fires before or after the triggering statement runs and whether it fires for each row that the triggering statement affects.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] If the trigger is created on a table or view, then the triggering event is composed of DML statements, and the trigger is called a DML trigger.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] If the trigger is created on a schema or the database, then the triggering event is composed of either DDL or database operation statements, and the trigger is called a system trigger.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] An INSTEAD OF trigger is either: A DML trigger created on a view or a system trigger defined on a CREATE statement.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The database fires the INSTEAD OF trigger instead of running the triggering statement.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The major datatypes in PL/SQL include NUMBER, CHAR, VARCHAR2, DATE and TIMESTAMP.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] To define a numeric variable, the programmer appends the variable type **NUMBER** to the name definition.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] To specify the (optional) precision (P) and the (optional) scale (S), one can further append these in round brackets, separated by a comma.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A selection of other data-types for numeric variables would include: binary_float, binary_double, dec, decimal, double precision, float, integer, int, numeric, real, small-int, binary_integer.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] To define a character variable, the programmer normally appends the variable type VARCHAR2 to the name definition.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] There follows in brackets the maximum number of characters the variable can store.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Other datatypes for character variables include: varchar, char, long, raw, long raw, nchar, nchar2, clob, blob, and bfile.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Date variables can contain date and time.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The time may be left out, but there is no way to define a variable that only contains the time.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] But there is no TIMESTAMP type that can contain fine-grained timestamp up to millisecond or nanosecond.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The `TO_DATE` function can be used to convert strings to date values.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] To convert the dates to strings one uses the function `TO_CHAR (date_string, format_string)`.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL also supports the use of ANSI date and interval literals.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Exceptions—errors during code execution—are of two types: user-defined and predefined.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Oracle Corporation has *predefined* several exceptions like `NO_DATA_FOUND`, `TOO_MANY_ROWS`, *etc.* Each exception has an SQL error number and SQL error message associated with it.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Programmers can access these by using the `SQLCODE` and `SQLERRM` functions.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] This syntax defines a variable of the type of the referenced column on the referenced tables.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] This sample program defines its own datatype, called *t_address*, which contains the fields *name, street, street_number* and *postcode*.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] So according to the example, we are able to copy the data from the database to the fields in the program.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Using this datatype the programmer has defined a variable called *v_address* and loaded it with data from the ADDRESS table.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The following code segment shows the IF-THEN-ELSIF-ELSE construct.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The ELSIF and ELSE parts are optional so it is possible to create simpler IF-THEN or, IF-THEN-ELSE constructs.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The CASE statement simplifies some large IF-THEN-ELSIF-ELSE structures.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL refers to arrays as "collections".
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Programmers must specify an upper limit for varrays, but need not for index-by tables or for nested tables.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The language includes several collection methods used to manipulate collection elements: for example FIRST, LAST, NEXT, PRIOR, EXTEND, TRIM, DELETE, etc.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Index-by tables can be used to simulate associative arrays, as in this example of a memo function for Ackermann's function in PL/SQL.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] With index-by tables, the array can be indexed by numbers or strings.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] It parallels a Java *map*, which comprises key-value pairs.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] There is only one dimension and it is unbounded.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] With nested tables the programmer needs to understand what is nested.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Here, a new type is created that may be composed of a number of components.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] That type can then be used to make a column in a table, and nested within that column are those components.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] With Varrays you need to understand that the word "variable" in the phrase "variable-size arrays" doesn't apply to the size of the array in the way you might think that it would.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The size the array is declared with is in fact fixed.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The number of elements in the array is variable up to the declared size.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Arguably then, variable-sized arrays aren't that variable in size.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A cursor is a pointer to a private SQL area that stores information coming from a SELECT or data manipulation language (DML) statement (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, or MERGE).
[src:plsql/pl-sql] A cursor holds the rows (one or more) returned by a SQL statement.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The set of rows the cursor holds is referred to as the active set.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] In a FOR loop, an explicit cursor shall be used if the query will be reused, otherwise an implicit cursor is preferred.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] If using a cursor inside a loop, use a FETCH is recommended when needing to bulk collect or when needing dynamic SQL.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] As a procedural language by definition, PL/SQL provides several iteration constructs, including basic LOOP statements, WHILE loops, FOR loops, and Cursor FOR loops.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Since Oracle 7.3 the REF CURSOR type was introduced to allow recordsets to be returned from stored procedures and functions.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Oracle 9i introduced the predefined SYS_REFCURSOR type, meaning we no longer have to define our own REF CURSOR types.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Loops can be terminated by using the `EXIT` keyword, or by raising an exception.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Cursor-for loops automatically open a cursor, read in their data and close the cursor again.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] As an alternative, the PL/SQL programmer can pre-define the cursor's SELECT-statement in advance to (for example) allow re-use or make the code more understandable (especially useful in the case of long or complex queries).
[src:plsql/pl-sql] While programmers can readily embed Data Manipulation Language (DML) statements directly into PL/SQL code using straightforward SQL statements, Data Definition Language (DDL) requires more complex "Dynamic SQL" statements in the PL/SQL code.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] However, DML statements underpin the majority of PL/SQL code in typical software applications.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] In the case of PL/SQL dynamic SQL, early versions of the Oracle Database required the use of a complicated Oracle `DBMS_SQL` package library.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] More recent versions have however introduced a simpler "Native Dynamic SQL", along with an associated `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` syntax.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL works analogously to the embedded procedural languages associated with other relational databases.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] For example, Sybase ASE and Microsoft SQL Server have Transact-SQL, PostgreSQL has PL/pgSQL (which emulates PL/SQL to an extent), MariaDB includes a PL/SQL compatibility parser, and IBM Db2 includes SQL Procedural Language, which conforms to the ISO SQL’s SQL/PSM standard.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The designers of PL/SQL modeled its syntax on that of Ada.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Both Ada and PL/SQL have Pascal as a common ancestor, and so PL/SQL also resembles Pascal in most aspects.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] However, the structure of a PL/SQL package does not resemble the basic Object Pascal program structure as implemented by a Borland Delphi or Free Pascal unit.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Programmers can define public and private global data-types, constants, and static variables in a PL/SQL package.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL also allows for the definition of classes and instantiating these as objects in PL/SQL code.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] This resembles usage in object-oriented programming languages like Object Pascal, C++ and Java.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL refers to a class as an "Abstract Data Type" (ADT) or "User Defined Type" (UDT), and defines it as an Oracle SQL data-type as opposed to a PL/SQL user-defined type, allowing its use in both the Oracle SQL Engine and the Oracle PL/SQL engine.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The constructor and methods of an Abstract Data Type are written in PL/SQL.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The resulting Abstract Data Type can operate as an object class in PL/SQL.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Such objects can also persist as column values in Oracle database tables.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] PL/SQL is fundamentally distinct from Transact-SQL, despite superficial similarities.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Porting code from one to the other usually involves non-trivial work, not only due to the differences in the feature sets of the two languages, but also due to the very significant differences in the way Oracle and SQL Server deal with concurrency and locking.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] The *StepSqlite* product is a PL/SQL compiler for the popular small database SQLite which supports a subset of PL/SQL syntax.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Oracle's Berkeley DB 11g R2 release added support for SQL based on the popular SQLite API by including a version of SQLite in Berkeley DB.
[src:plsql/pl-sql] Consequently, StepSqlite can also be used as a third-party tool to run PL/SQL code on Berkeley DB.
[src:plsql/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:plsql/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:plsql/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:plsql/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:plsql/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:plsql/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:plsql/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:plsql/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:plsql/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:plsql/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:plsql/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:plsql/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:plsql/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:plsql/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:plsql/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:plsql/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:plsql/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:plsql/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:plsql/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:plsql/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:plsql/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:plsql/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:plsql/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:plsql/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:plsql/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:plsql/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:plsql/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:plsql/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:plsql/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:plsql/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:plsql/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:plsql/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:plsql/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:plsql/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:plsql/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:plsql/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:plsql/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:plsql/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:plsql/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:plsql/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:plsql/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:plsql/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:plsql/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:plsql/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:plsql/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:plsql/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:plsql/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:plsql/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:plsql/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:plsql/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:plsql/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:plsql/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:plsql/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:plsql/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:plsql/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:plsql/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:plsql/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:plsql/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:plsql/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:plsql/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:plsql/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:plsql/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:plsql/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:plsql/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:plsql/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] A **stored procedure** (also termed **prc**, **proc**, **storp**, **sproc**, **StoPro**, **StoredProc**, **StoreProc**, **sp**, or **SP**) is a subroutine available to applications that access a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Such procedures are stored in the database data dictionary.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Uses for stored procedures include data-validation (integrated into the database) or access-control mechanisms.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Furthermore, stored procedures can consolidate and centralize logic that was originally implemented in applications.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] To save time and memory, extensive or complex processing that requires execution of several SQL statements can be saved into stored procedures, and all applications call the procedures.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] One can use nested stored procedures by executing one stored procedure from within another.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may return result sets, i.e., the results of a `SELECT` statement.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Such result sets can be processed using cursors, by other stored procedures, by associating a result-set locator, or by applications.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may also contain declared variables for processing data and cursors that allow it to loop through multiple rows in a table.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored-procedure flow-control statements typically include `IF`, `WHILE`, `LOOP`, `REPEAT`, and `CASE` statements, and more.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can receive variables, return results or modify variables and return them, depending on how and where the variable is declared.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures are similar to user-defined functions (UDFs).
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] The major difference is that UDFs can be used like any other expression within SQL statements, whereas stored procedures must be invoked using the `CALL` statement.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] The exact and correct implementation of stored procedures varies from one database system to the other.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Most major database vendors support them in some form.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Depending on the database system, stored procedures can be implemented in a variety of programming languages, for example SQL, Java, C, or C++.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures written in non-SQL languages may or may not execute SQL statements themselves.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] The increasing adoption of stored procedures led to the introduction of procedural elements to the SQL language in the SQL:1999 and SQL:2003 standards in the part SQL/PSM.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] That made SQL an imperative programming language.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Most database systems offer proprietary and vendor-specific extensions, exceeding SQL/PSM.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] A standard specification for Java stored procedures exists as well as SQL/JRT.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] remove all or part of the compiling overhead that is typically needed when software applications send inline (dynamic) SQL queries to a database.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] and other methods to avoid repetitively compiling dynamic SQL statements.) Also, while they avoid some pre-compiled SQL, statements add to the complexity of creating an optimal execution plan because not all arguments of the SQL statement are supplied at compile time.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Depending on the specific database implementation and configuration, mixed performance results will be seen from stored procedures versus generic queries or user defined functions.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] In a production system, this typically means that the procedures run entirely on a specialized database server with direct access to the data.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] The benefit is that it saves network costs, which stands out when a series of SQL statements are involved.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] as an API in the database, which can simplify data management and reduce the need to encode the logic elsewhere in client programs.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] This can result in a lesser likelihood of data corruption by faulty client programs.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] In many systems, stored procedures can be granted access rights to the database that users who execute those procedures do not directly have.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can be used to protect against injection attacks.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedure parameters will be treated as data even if an attacker inserts SQL commands.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Also, some DBMS will check the parameter's type.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] However, a stored procedure that in turn generates dynamic SQL using the input is still vulnerable to SQL injections unless proper precautions are taken.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] In some systems, stored procedures can be used to control transaction management; in others, stored procedures run inside a transaction such that transactions are effectively transparent to them.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can also be invoked from a database trigger or a condition handler.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] For example, a stored procedure may be triggered by an insert on a specific table, or update of a specific field in a table, and the code inside the stored procedure would be executed.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Writing stored procedures as condition handlers also allows database administrators to track errors in the system with greater detail by using stored procedures to catch the errors and record some audit information in the database or an external resource like a file.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Prepared statements take an ordinary statement or query and parameterize it so that different literal values can be used at a later time.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Like stored procedures, they are stored on the server for efficiency and provide some protection from SQL injection attacks.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Although simpler and more declarative, prepared statements are not ordinarily written to use procedural logic and cannot operate on variables.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Because of their simple interface and client-side implementations, prepared statements are more widely reusable between DBMS.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Smart contract is a term applied to executable code stored on a blockchain as opposed to an RDBMS.
[src:plsql/stored-procedure] Despite the execution result consensus mechanisms of public blockchain networks differing in principle from traditional private or federated databases, they perform ostensibly the same function as stored procedures, albeit usually with a sense of value transaction.
